        <div class=3D"post-body">
            <span id=3D"hs_cos_wrapper_post_body" class=3D"hs_cos_wrapper h=
s_cos_wrapper_meta_field hs_cos_wrapper_type_rich_text" style=3D"" data-hs-=
cos-general-type=3D"meta_field" data-hs-cos-type=3D"rich_text"><h5>Work Pro=
cesses are Everywhere&nbsp;&nbsp;</h5>
<p><span style=3D"background-color: transparent;">Whether we=E2=80=99re awa=
re of it or not, there is a sequence of steps for every task we do - even s=
imple activities like washing hands, brushing teeth, and making dinner. &nb=
sp;At work, some organizations use standard operating procedures (SOPs), wh=
ich are just <a href=3D"https://blog.thinkreliability.com/levels-of-detail-=
work-processes-as-systems" rel=3D"noopener">work processes</a> that have be=
en written down. &nbsp;Do we need an SOP to follow every morning and night =
to brush our teeth? Probably not. &nbsp;Do we need SOPs at work to ensure c=
ertain tasks are carried out consistently and accurately? &nbsp;Probably so=
. &nbsp;Process mapping is visual like the Cause Mapping</span><sup style=
=3D"background-color: transparent;">=C2=AE</sup><span style=3D"background-c=
olor: transparent;"> method, but instead of capturing causes, it captures t=
he steps within a task.</span></p>
<p><!--more--></p>
<h5><span style=3D"background-color: transparent;">Making Toast</span></h5>
<p><span style=3D"background-color: transparent;">Watch Tom Wujec=E2=80=99s=
 excellent&nbsp;</span><a href=3D"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3D_vS_b7c=
Jn2A" rel=3D"noopener" target=3D"_blank">TED talk</a>&nbsp;<span style=3D"b=
ackground-color: transparent;">on problem-solving titled </span><span style=
=3D"background-color: transparent;">=E2=80=9CGot a wicked problem? First, t=
ell me how you make toast.=E2=80=9D &nbsp;Wujec demonstrates how the simple=
st task of making toast can actually be carried out in an unlimited number =
of ways. &nbsp;Tom asks people to draw instructions for how to make toast u=
sing no words.</span></p>
<p>His exercise illustrates an interesting point. &nbsp;Different people ha=
ve different perspectives on how toast is made. &nbsp;If you ask 20 differe=
nt people to write instructions on how to do something, you=E2=80=99ll like=
ly receive 20 different answers. &nbsp;Some instructions may be complicated=
 and have many steps. Others may only have 3 to 5 steps. Each person may be=
 able to accomplish the assigned task, but each person may use a different =
work process.</p>
<h5>Different Process Maps</h5>
<p>To demonstrate this, I asked three different people to build a <a href=
=3D"https://www.thinkreliability.com/services/work-process-reliability/">pr=
ocess map</a> for how they make toast. Here are the results.</p>
<p><strong><span style=3D"background-color: transparent;">Version 1:&nbsp;&=
nbsp;</span></strong><span style=3D"background-color: transparent;">This Pr=
ocess Map is straightforward. &nbsp;It=E2=80=99s linear.&nbsp; There are no=
 decision points. You just make toast.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;<img src=3D"https://blog.thinkreliability.com/hs-fs/hubfs/process-=
map-toast-v1.jpg?width=3D702&amp;name=3Dprocess-map-toast-v1.jpg" alt=3D"pr=
ocess-map-toast-v1" width=3D"702" style=3D"width: 702px;"></p>
<p><strong>Version 2:&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;<span style=3D"background-color: =
transparent;">This process map is also straightforward. Although this versi=
on does offer an option to start over if one is not satisfied with the firs=
t attempt at making toast.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<img src=3D"https://blog.thinkreliability.com/hs-fs/hubfs/process-map-toast=
-v2.jpg?width=3D1000&amp;name=3Dprocess-map-toast-v2.jpg" alt=3D"process-ma=
p-toast-v2" width=3D"1000" style=3D"width: 1000px; display: block; margin: =
0px auto;">
<p><strong>Version 3:</strong>&nbsp;<span style=3D"background-color: transp=
arent;">This process map has more steps.&nbsp; In this household, there are=
 different points of view for making toast: the dad=E2=80=99s method and th=
e daughter=E2=80=99s method.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"background-color: transparent;"><img src=3D"https://blog.=
thinkreliability.com/hs-fs/hubfs/process-map-toast-v3.jpg?width=3D1280&amp;=
name=3Dprocess-map-toast-v3.jpg" alt=3D"process-map-toast-v3" width=3D"1280=
" style=3D"width: 1280px;"></span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><span style=3D"background-color: transparent;">For a better view, click =
